TY  - JOUR
T1  - Private Profits and Public Health: Does Advertising of Smoking Cessation Products Encourage Smokers to Quit?
AU  - Avery, Rosemary
AU  - Kenkel, Donald
AU  - Lillard, Dean R.
AU  - Mathios, Alan
Y1  - 2007/06/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/520065
DO  - 10.1086/520065
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 447
EP  - 481
VL  - 115
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study the impact of smoking cessation product advertising. To measure potential exposure, we link survey data on magazine?reading habits and smoking behavior with an archive of print advertisements. We find that smokers who are exposed to more advertising are more likely to attempt to quit and to successfully quit. While some increased quitting involves product purchases, we find that product advertisements also prompt cold turkey quitting. Identifying the causal impact of advertising is difficult because advertisers target consumers. Although reverse causality could bias our estimates upward, our baseline results are not sensitive to a series of checks.
AB  - We study the impact of smoking cessation product advertising. To measure potential exposure, we link survey data on magazine?reading habits and smoking behavior with an archive of print advertisements. We find that smokers who are exposed to more advertising are more likely to attempt to quit and to successfully quit. While some increased quitting involves product purchases, we find that product advertisements also prompt cold turkey quitting. Identifying the causal impact of advertising is difficult because advertisers target consumers. Although reverse causality could bias our estimates upward, our baseline results are not sensitive to a series of checks.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/520065
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/520065
Y2  - 2024/03/22
